ce:section.ce:para:
Accurate prediction of lithium-ion battery thermal behavior using thermal modeling depends on the accuracy of model parameters. In lumped thermal models, the heat equation is solved to obtain the temperature field across the cell domain, which requires accurate knowledge of thermophysical parameters. Thermal conductivity (k), specific heat capacity (c

                        P
                     ), and density (ρ) are the main thermophysical parameters used in the transient thermal simulations of lithium-ion batteries. A detailed description of the proposed methodology and adopted procedures is presented in the following sections.

Specimen for in-plane (k

                              z
                           ) measurements was prepared by cutting out an anode-separator-cathode repeat unit in the form of rectangular strips. Multiple strips were joined at the ends and rolled into a spiral over a cylinder having a diameter matching the inner diameter of the specimen. Strips were rolled until the desired outer diameter is reached (Fig. 1b). Specimen inner and outer diameter was taken to be 10 mm and 40 mm respectively, Thickness (height) of the specimen was kept between 10 mm and 15 mm. Specimen to measure through-plane component of thermal conductivity (k

                              r
                           ) was prepared using a hollow cylindrical punch-press of 40 mm diameter to blank out circular sheets of anode-separator-cathode sequences. Cut-through repeat units were stacked together to make the required thickness of 10–15 mm, as elucidated in Fig. 1a. The same setup (Section 2.1.4) can be used for cylindrical cell configuration with small modifications in the specimen preparation procedure. For example, a specimen to measure axial thermal conductivity (k

                              z
                           ) of a cylindrical cell jellyroll can be prepared by slicing a portion through the jellyroll. Specimen for radial thermal conductivity (k

                              r
                           ) measurement can be prepared by unwinding the dried jellyroll and following the procedure for the preparation of the specimen for through-plane measurements described above.

In addition to thermal conductivity (k) and heat capacity (c

                           P
                        ), density (ρ) is another important parameter required for transient thermal simulations of lithium-ion batteries. Density is measured in (kg∙m−3) in the SI system of units. The density of the electrode layers was measured using the specimen for through-plane thermal conductivity measurements. Since density is measured as the mass per unit volume of the given material, knowing mass and volume, the density of the specimen could easily be calculated.

Lower thermal conductivity in through-plane (k

                           r
                        ) direction as compared to that in the in-plane direction (dry and wetted) can be explained by discontinuities in the heat flow path due to the presence of layers of different materials, some of which have very low thermal conductivity, that is, separator. Moreover, air is trapped between the layers, restricting the flow of heat in the through-plane direction. Higher thermal conductivity in the in-plane direction (k

                           z
                        ) is due to the presence of highly conductive copper and aluminum, where the heat flow path is not crossed and the phase is continuous.

It can be noticed that a significantly lower through-plane thermal conductivity (k

                           r
                        ) resulted when dry specimens were used. This can be explained by the fact that, in dry specimens, air occupies active material pores and spaces between the adjacent electrode layers. This significantly increases contact resistance in the case of through-plane measurements. On the other hand, the effect of electrolyte is not dominant in the case of in-plane thermal conductivity (k

                           z
                        ). Since in the specimen used for in-plane thermal conductivity measurements electrode layers do not cross each other’s path, and the heat transport media is rather continuous. Hence, wetting with electrolyte does not improve heat transfer in the in-plane direction.
